      <bioghist id="aspace_c2362b2ab1b6125e49c72a92e9e3c1ed">
         <head>Ruth Wetmore Newcomb</head>
         <p>Ruth Wetmore Newcomb was born in New London, Connecticut on March 28, 1890. She attended Williams Memorial Institute and the Abbot Academy at Phillips Andover. After returning home from school, she spent time with her uncle, James Newcomb and his wife, Elizabeth Wilmont Newcomb.</p>
         <p>In 1914, Ruth Wetmore Newcomb was invited to join Elizabeth Wilmont Newcomb on a Grand Tour aboard the S. S. Rotterdam. She was accompanied by her friend Helen Whiton on the voyage.</p>
         <p>Throughout her life, Wetmore Newcomb continued to travel. She also taught ceramics and crafts in Connecticut, and engaged in architectural preservation efforts around the New London, Connecticut area.</p>
         <p>Ruth Wetmore Newcomb died on March 9, 1984.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_2f65c5429820ade945a5eae96d4e7c36">
